  "verdict": "FAIL",
  "violations": [
    {
      "edge": "Triggers → Maladaptive Strategies",
      "explanation": "The vignette does include triggers and maladaptive strategies, but not in a single sentence with explicit causal language connecting the trigger to the strategy in the required direction. The closest sentence is: \"The sight of blood or the sound of cars pulls up the same harsh self-appraisal, and those appraisals in turn make him more vigilant for the very cues he dreads.\" This supports Triggers → Negative Appraisals and Negative Appraisals → Triggers, not Triggers → Maladaptive Strategies. It would need a sentence like \"The sight of blood leads him to avoid eye contact\" with the causal connector between trigger and strategy.",
      "quote": "\"The sight of blood or the sound of cars pulls up the same harsh self-appraisal, and those appraisals in turn make him more vigilant for the very cues he dreads.\""
    },
    {
      "edge": "Triggers → Memory",
      "explanation": "Triggers and memory are both present, but there is no single sentence where a trigger explicitly causes memory in the required direction. The sentence \"When Ravi recalls the event, he describes being thrown back into the same terror he felt at the time.\" shows Memory causing re-experiencing/affect, not Triggers causing Memory. A required match would need something like \"The sight of blood triggers memories of the event.\"",
      "quote": "\"When Ravi recalls the event, he describes being thrown back into the same terror he felt at the time.\""
    },
    {
      "edge": "Triggers → Negative Appraisals",
      "explanation": "The vignette does contain a sentence that nearly matches this, but the causal direction is actually explicit as Triggers causing appraisals: \"The sight of blood or the sound of cars pulls up the same harsh self-appraisal.\" However, because the phrase refers to \"self-appraisal\" rather than the specified component label \"Negative Appraisals,\" and the rest of the sentence continues to a different relation, I am not counting it as a clear enough single-sentence match under the strict synonym requirement. A safer required-graph match would need explicit wording like \"Blood and car sounds lead him to negative appraisals about himself.\"",
      "quote": "\"The sight of blood or the sound of cars pulls up the same harsh self-appraisal, and those appraisals in turn make him more vigilant for the very cues he dreads.\""
    },
    {
      "edge": "Negative Appraisals → Maladaptive Strategies",
      "explanation": "This edge is present in the sentence: \"The sight of blood or the sound of cars pulls up the same harsh self-appraisal, and those appraisals in turn make him more vigilant for the very cues he dreads.\" The causal language \"in turn make\" sits between appraisals and vigilance. However, \"more vigilant\" is closer to an attentional response than the required \"Maladaptive Strategies\" label, and the sentence does not explicitly name the full strategy set (avoidance, withdrawal, eye contact avoidance, etc.) as the direct effect of appraisals. Under the strict standard, I am marking this as missing because the required component is not clearly and directly identified as the outcome of the causal connector.",
      "quote": "\"The sight of blood or the sound of cars pulls up the same harsh self-appraisal, and those appraisals in turn make him more vigilant for the very cues he dreads.\""
    },
    {
      "edge": "Negative Appraisals → Memory",
      "explanation": "The vignette has memory eliciting appraisals, not the other way around. For example: \"When Ravi recalls the event, he describes being thrown back into the same terror he felt at the time.\" This is Memory → (re-experiencing/affect), and the later line \"the sight of blood or the sound of cars pulls up the same harsh self-appraisal\" does not link appraisals to memory. A required sentence would need explicit causal wording such as \"His harsh self-appraisals bring the memory back.\"",
      "quote": "\"When Ravi recalls the event, he describes being thrown back into the same terror he felt at the time.\""
    },
    {
      "edge": "Negative Appraisals → Triggers",
      "explanation": "The closest support is: \"The sight of blood or the sound of cars pulls up the same harsh self-appraisal, and those appraisals in turn make him more vigilant for the very cues he dreads.\" This clearly expresses the opposite direction: appraisals increase vigilance for cues, not the cues themselves as the outcome of appraisals. Since the required edge is specifically Negative Appraisals → Triggers, and the text does not say appraisals cause the triggers to appear or intensify, I mark it missing.",
      "quote": "\"The sight of blood or the sound of cars pulls up the same harsh self-appraisal, and those appraisals in turn make him more vigilant for the very cues he dreads.\""
    },
    {
      "edge": "Memory → Maladaptive Strategies",
      "explanation": "The vignette includes memory and maladaptive strategies, but no single sentence explicitly states that memory causes the strategies. The closest sentence is: \"When Ravi recalls the event, he describes being thrown back into the same terror he felt at the time.\" This describes memory causing terror, not avoidance, withdrawal, or other strategies. A matching sentence would need something like \"Remembering the event leads him to avoid eye contact.\"",
      "quote": "\"When Ravi recalls the event, he describes being thrown back into the same terror he felt at the time.\""
    },
    {
      "edge": "Memory → Negative Appraisals",
      "explanation": "There is no single sentence where recalling the event explicitly causes negative appraisals. The sentence \"When Ravi recalls the event, he describes being thrown back into the same terror he felt at the time.\" only links memory to terror. A valid match would require explicit wording such as \"Recalling the event makes him think he is defective.\"",
      "quote": "\"When Ravi recalls the event, he describes being thrown back into the same terror he felt at the time.\""
    },
    {
      "edge": "Memory → Triggers",
      "explanation": "Memory is described, and triggers are described, but the vignette does not state in one sentence that memory causes triggers. The sentence \"When Ravi recalls the event, he describes being thrown back into the same terror he felt at the time.\" does not mention triggers; conversely, \"The sight of blood or the sound of cars pulls up the same harsh self-appraisal\" is trigger-driven appraisals. A required sentence would need something like \"His memories make him notice blood and car sounds as triggers.\"",
      "quote": "\"When Ravi recalls the event, he describes being thrown back into the same terror he felt at the time.\""
    },
    {
      "edge": "Maladaptive Strategies → Memory",
      "explanation": "The vignette states that after scanning, he withdraws and avoids eye contact, leaving him alone with more time to think he is damaged and failed, but it does not explicitly say those strategies cause memory. The closest sentence is: \"Once he is scanning in that way, he withdraws further, avoids eye contact, and stays away from religious spaces, which leaves him alone with more time to think that he is damaged and that he failed.\" This links strategies to rumination/negative appraisal, not memory. A required match would need explicit language like \"Avoiding others brings the memory back.\"",
      "quote": "\"Once he is scanning in that way, he withdraws further, avoids eye contact, and stays away from religious spaces, which leaves him alone with more time to think that he is damaged and that he failed.\""
    },
    {
      "edge": "Maladaptive Strategies → Negative Appraisals",
      "explanation": "This edge is present in the sentence: \"Once he is scanning in that way, he withdraws further, avoids eye contact, and stays away from religious spaces, which leaves him alone with more time to think that he is damaged and that he failed.\" The causal phrase \"which leaves him alone with more time to think\" sits between the avoidance behaviors and the negative appraisals. This is a clear causal link from maladaptive strategies to negative appraisals.",
      "quote": "\"Once he is scanning in that way, he withdraws further, avoids eye contact, and stays away from religious spaces, which leaves him alone with more time to think that he is damaged and that he failed.\""
    }
  ]
